\begin_layout Standard
Through above experiments, we have empirically confirmed our hypothesis
 that for a 
\begin_inset Formula $1-$
\end_inset

dimensional normal distribution, the mean time until convergence (in terms
 of ergodic averages) increases as variance increases.
 We have looked at two directions: first fixing a bound 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and comparing the mean times for different values of variances, next varying
 the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

's for each fixed variance and then comparing the results for different
 variances.
 In both cases, we attain the desired results.
 Although depending on the choice of the functions we consider, the computationa
l cost and the mean times may vary quite significantly, we invariably get
 increasing times as variance increases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now ready to move on to a multi 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional setting.
 Let us first consider the case of a 
\begin_inset Formula $d-$
\end_inset

dimensional normal distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $d-$
\end_inset

independent components.
 For simplicity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset

.
 From a theoretical point of view, generating two
\begin_inset Formula $(d)$
\end_inset

 processes for two
\begin_inset Formula $(d)$
\end_inset

 coordinates is the same as generating one process for both
\begin_inset Formula $(d)$
\end_inset

 due to the properties of the Poisson Process (can you explain this part
 further?) Hence, we are able to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $2(d)$
\end_inset

 separate processes and so it is natural to conjecture that the rate of
 convergence of the process will correspond to that of the process with
 the largest variance.
 This means that in terms of the time it takes for the whole process to
 converge, instead of looking at the overall process, we need simply look
 at the one-dimensional process with the largest variance, and we know the
 time as we have acquired this in our previous discussion.
 In this respect, for 
\begin_inset Formula $d-$
\end_inset

dimensional normal distributions, it is more interesting to look at how
 convergence rates change if there is any correlation.
 So again, to simplify and gain more insight, we will first restrict to
 the simplest case of 
\begin_inset Formula $d=2$
\end_inset

 with a fixed correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 between the two processes and investigate how 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 influences convergence.
 
